<span id="freeTextContainer8773390734173682192">Smell, they say, is the strongest of the senses.<br/><br/>Hmmmmm,<br/><br/>I remember a time, years ago, on the beach.<br/>I could smell the lake, the night air<br/>Feel the Harley spinning out of control as it hit the sand. No pain just<br/>The smell of wet leather and silk <br/>Bob Seger singing<br/>Moonlit endless sand<br/>The taste of beer and cigarettes<br/>His scent……..mine….mingled.<br/><br/>That’s the thing about smell; it commands an immediate and visceral response. It is instinctive, automatic; void of conscious thought or will, all the while affect</span>
  <span id="freeText8773390734173682192" style="display:none">Smell, they say, is the strongest of the senses.<br /><br />Hmmmmm,<br /><br />I remember a time, years ago, on the beach.<br />I could smell the lake, the night air<br />Feel the Harley spinning out of control as it hit the sand. No pain just<br />The smell of wet leather and silk <br />Bob Seger singing<br />Moonlit endless sand<br />The taste of beer and cigarettes<br />His scent……..mine….mingled.<br /><br />That’s the thing about smell; it commands an immediate and visceral response. It is instinctive, automatic; void of conscious thought or will, all the while affecting a wide range of behaviours; emotion, motivation …..memory. <br /><br />Perfume is an olfactory experience. Murder most monstrous is afoot. Suskind takes you on a bloody, smelly, insane quest.<br /></span>
